  "texts": [
    "62 As a general-purpose rule, GR1 has a great appeal in virtue of its computational efficiency: simply check whether you would accept an action based on your preferences.",
    "Prima facie, it would also capture many preferences that are commonly shared among self-interested agents in the natural world, e.g., to increase one's pleasure and reduce one's suffering.",
    "As such, it would therefore work to prevent actions that, for instance, directly cause harm.",
    "However, the major problem with GR1 is that it does not account for differences in preferences between agents, and how actions affect the preferences of agents in different ways.",
    "It is therefore susceptible to counter-examples: e.g., a judge should not send a criminal to prison, because the judge himself does not want to go to prison."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}